The error message indicates that 'Flask' is not defined in your script, which means you haven't imported it into your Python environment. Here is a simple Flask application with /hello route:

```json
{
  "files": [
    {
      "path": "app.py",
      "content": "from flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\n@app.route('/hello')\ndef hello():\n    return 'Hello, World!'"
    }
  ],
  "commands": ["export FLASK_APP=app.py", "flask run"]
}
```

This JSON object contains two parts: `files` and `commands`. The `files` part is an array of file objects, each with a `path` (the location to save the file) and `content` (the content of the file). In this case, we're creating a new Python script named 'app.py', which imports Flask from its standard library, creates an instance of it, defines a route '/hello', and returns a simple string when that route is accessed.

The `commands` part is an array of shell commands to run after the files have been updated. In this case, we're setting the FLASK_APP environment variable to 'app.py' (the name of our Flask application), then running it with flask run.

